# 🐞 bug report

### Affected Package

The issue is caused by package @angular/router or @angular/common.

### Is this a regression?

No.

### Description

When using Location.go (`@angular/common`), Angular's routing starts behaving strangely when using the browser's back and forward button.

After calling `location.go`, using the browser back button doesn't register query changes. I expected this behaviour because I'm not using the router to navigate.  

However, using the browser forward/back buttons after this **does** register query changes. The same happens when calling `location.go` twice before using the browser buttons.

I can understand the routing may be needed because you could use the history to navigate to a different page, but then I'd expect the same behaviour on the first entry (on the first location push and the first back press).  

In my use case, I am trying to catch the pop state manually when within the same page. This works nicely for every entry added, but the inconsistent behaviour of the router is getting in the way. When navigating to the same url (with a different query), I'd like to prevent Angular's routing and handle it myself with `location.subscribe`.  
Perhaps this is possible by manipulating the history state using `history.pushState`? My attempts there failed.

## 🔬 Minimal Reproduction
<!--
Please create and share minimal reproduction of the issue starting with this template: https://stackblitz.com/fork/angular-issue-repro2
-->

https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-router-basic-example-5kgjqs

> Note: the embedded demo seems to behave differently and starts reloading the page entirely, which I assume is a stackblitz problem. **Please view the demo at https://angular-router-basic-example-5kgjqs.stackblitz.io/start**, which behaves the same as my local project (on Chrome, Firefox and Edge).

*  Press <kbd>Push</kbd> to add a new query to the browser history using `location.go`.
* Press the browser back button and witness no query change.
* Press the browser forward/back buttons and witness a query change every time you navigate.

